column4: The implant is a tiny, flexible rod (the size of a matchstick) that is inserted under the skin of your upper arm to prevent pregnancy. It is a long-acting hormonal methods.
column6: It is inserted by a doctor or nurse under the skin of your upper arm. Once it’s in, you can’t feel it unless you try to find it with your fingers.
column12: Talk with your doctor first and try to avoid having sex or use another contraceptive method until you confirm remedial actions with your doctor.
column14: A. If the implant is fitted during the first 5 days of your menstrual cycle you'll be immediately protected against becoming pregnant. B. If it's fitted on any other day of your menstrual cycle, you'll need to use additional contraceptives (such as condoms) for the first week.
column15: The implant can be removed at any time by a trained doctor or nurse.
column16: A trained doctor or nurses will make a tiny cut in your skin to gently pull the implant out.
column17: The process only takes a few minutes to remove, and a local anesthetic will be used.
column18: Once the implant is removed your ability to get pregnant quickly returns.

column21: The implant releases the hormone progestogen into your bloodstream, which prevents the release of an egg each month (ovulation) to prevent pregnancy.
column22: Serious problems with Nexplanon are rare, but they include arm pain that lasts for longer than a few days, an infection in the arm that needs medicine, or a scar on your arm where the implant goes.
